{"theory_name":"Intrinsic Reference Frame Theory (IRFT)","core_claim":"Subjective experience is the brain's establishment of an intrinsic, self-generated reference frame that converts otherwise observer-dependent neural variables into internally well-defined relational quantities; consciousness occurs exactly when a single dominant intrinsic reference frame exists and organizes neural activity into a coherent "within-system" perspective.","mechanism":"Neural activity is physically measurable from the outside as amplitudes, firing rates, and synchrony patterns, but these quantities are not intrinsically meaningful to the system unless they are expressed relative to a stable internal standard. IRFT proposes that consciousness arises when corticothalamic and brainstem circuits generate a metastable, low-dimensional dynamical reference (an intrinsic phase/coordinate frame) that (i) provides a common relational origin (e.g., a phase zero / coordinate anchor) and (ii) continuously re-expresses distributed neural signals as relations to that origin. 

In this view, qualia are not "information," "predictions," "broadcast contents," or "higher-order judgments." They are the specific set of gauge-invariant relational observables defined by the active intrinsic frame (i.e., what remains the same under internal reparameterizations of the neural code). The "what-it-is-like" character corresponds to the particular symmetry-breaking choice of reference frame among many physically possible frames; once a system fixes one frame, it has an irreducibly indexical (first-person) set of relations that cannot be fully captured by a description that does not adopt that same internal frame. 

Hard-problem move: IRFT identifies phenomenal character with the system's own internally fixed relational ontology (the intrinsic frame and its invariants). An external description can list neural states, but it does not instantiate the same symmetry-broken internal reference; thus it can predict reports/behavior without thereby being the experience. Experience is the physical act of reference-frame fixing and the resulting relational field, not an additional substance.","predictions":["Dominant-Frame Criterion: Across wakefulness, dreaming, anesthesia, seizures, and minimally conscious states, consciousness will track the presence of a single dominant intrinsic reference frame measurable as a stable global phase/coordinate anchor across widely separated neural populations (quantified by a new metric: reference-frame dominance, RFD). Loss of consciousness will correspond to either (a) collapse of any stable anchor or (b) fragmentation into multiple competing anchors (low RFD), even if overall functional connectivity or information-theoretic integration remains high.","Frame-Swap Invariance: If two stimulus conditions are engineered so that neural codes differ at the level of raw activity patterns but preserve the same gauge-invariant relational structure with respect to the intrinsic frame, subjects will report highly similar qualitative experience despite large differences in decodable "content" from standard population codes. Conversely, manipulations that preserve decodable content but alter relational invariants (via targeted phase-reference perturbation) will change reported qualia disproportionately.","Causal Perturbation of the Anchor: Closed-loop stimulation that stabilizes or reinstates the intrinsic reference frame (e.g., enforcing a coherent global phase anchor between specific corticothalamic hubs) will restore conscious level more effectively than stimulation matched for firing rate or connectivity changes but that fails to restore frame dominance. This effect should be observed even when sensory input and report are held constant (e.g., in anesthetized animals using no-report neural markers)."],"explanatory_power":"Explains (i) unity of consciousness as the existence of one dominant intrinsic frame; (ii) dissociation/split phenomena (certain seizures, depersonalization, some psychedelic fragmentation) as transient competition among multiple frames; (iii) dreaming as a preserved intrinsic frame with weak anchoring to external sensorimotor constraints (frame intact, coupling altered); (iv) why some highly recurrent/integrated neural activity can still be unconscious if it fails to lock into a dominant frame; (v) why first-person perspective is inherently indexical: it is the symmetry-broken internal coordinate system that makes any state 'for the system.'","novelty_justification":"IRFT is not reducible to Global Workspace (it does not define consciousness as broadcasting/access), IIT (it does not equate consciousness with quantity/structure of integrated information), HOT (it does not require higher-order representations or metacognitive attribution), Predictive Processing (it does not define consciousness as prediction error minimization or generative modeling), or Attention Schema (it does not posit an internal model of attention as constitutive). Its primitive explanatory posit is different: consciousness is the physical establishment of an intrinsic reference frame via symmetry breaking, and phenomenal qualities are identified with gauge-invariant relational observables defined by that frame. The theory's key measurable construct (reference-frame dominance/fragmentation) and its "frame-swap invariance" prediction are specific and distinct from existing hallmark predictions (global ignition, phi/PCI-like integration metrics, higher-order report dependence, prediction-error signatures, or attention-model accuracy)."}
